In [300]:
def compress(image,k):
    n,p,z = image.shape
    R = image[:,:,0]
    G = image[:,:,1]
    B = image[:,:,2]
    
    U_R, S_R, Vt_R = la.svd(R, full_matrices=False)
    U_G, S_G, Vt_G = la.svd(G, full_matrices=False)
    U_B, S_B, Vt_B = la.svd(B, full_matrices=False)
       
    S_kR = S_R.copy()
    S_kR = S_kR[:k]
    S_kR_diag = np.diag(S_kR)
    U_R = U_R[:,:k]
    Vt_R = Vt_R[:k,:]
    
    S_kG = S_G.copy()
    S_kG = S_kG[:k]
    S_kG_diag = np.diag(S_kG)
    U_G = U_G[:,:k]
    Vt_G = Vt_G[:k,:]
    
    S_kB = S_B.copy()
    S_kB = S_kB[:k]
    S_kB_diag = np.diag(S_kB)
    U_B = U_B[:,:k]
    Vt_B = Vt_B[:k,:]
    
    X_Rk = U_R@S_kR_diag@Vt_R
    X_Gk = U_G@S_kG_diag@Vt_G
    X_Bk = U_B@S_kB_diag@Vt_B

    reconst_matrix=np.zeros((n,p,z))
    reconst_matrix[:,:,0] = X_Rk
    reconst_matrix[:,:,1] = X_Gk
    reconst_matrix[:,:,2] = X_Bk
    
    reconst_matrix = np.array(reconst_matrix).astype(np.int32)
    
    return reconst_matrix

It seems that the relative error exponentially decays with higher values of k for rank approximation. It's hard to tell visually from the graph, but there seems to be an inflection point somewhere around 20-40 for the rank approximation where the relative error seems to plateau out, indicating that most of the necessary information is within this range of singular values.

def compress_c(image,k):
    n,p,z = image.shape
    R = image[:,:,0]
    G = image[:,:,1]
    B = image[:,:,2]
    
    U_R, S_R, Vt_R = la.svd(R, full_matrices=False)
    U_G, S_G, Vt_G = la.svd(G, full_matrices=False)
    U_B, S_B, Vt_B = la.svd(B, full_matrices=False)
       
    S_kR = S_R.copy()
    S_kR = S_kR[:k]
    S_kR_diag = np.diag(S_kR)
    U_R = U_R[:,:k]
    Vt_R = Vt_R[:k,:]
    
    S_kG = S_G.copy()
    S_kG = S_kG[:k]
    S_kG_diag = np.diag(S_kG)
    U_G = U_G[:,:k]
    Vt_G = Vt_G[:k,:]
    
    S_kB = S_B.copy()
    S_kB = S_kB[:k]
    S_kB_diag = np.diag(S_kB)
    U_B = U_B[:,:k]
    Vt_B = Vt_B[:k,:]
    
    X_Rk = U_R@S_kR_diag@Vt_R
    X_Gk = U_G@S_kG_diag@Vt_G
    X_Bk = U_B@S_kB_diag@Vt_B

    reconst_matrix=np.zeros((n,p,z))
    reconst_matrix[:,:,0] = X_Rk
    reconst_matrix[:,:,1] = X_Gk
    reconst_matrix[:,:,2] = X_Bk
    
    reconst_matrix = np.array(reconst_matrix).astype(np.int32)
    
    U_c, S_c, Vt_c = la.svd(reconst_matrix, full_matrices=False)

    return U_R.size, Vt_R.size

k_values = np.arange(500)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5))

axes[0].set_title('U Compression Rate')
axes[0].set_ylabel('U Compression Rate')
axes[0].set_xlabel('Rank Approximation K')

axes[1].plot(k_values,compressionV)
axes[1].set_title('V Compression Rate')
axes[1].set_ylabel('V Compression Rate')
axes[1].set_xlabel('Rank Approximation K')

plt.show()

Both graphs show a linear trend, where the compression rate linearly depends on the k value, up until around k=375. This makes sense, because as the value of k increases by 1, you are increasing the numerator in the comrpession rate equation ever so slightly with an increase of 1 more singular value and one more column/row of U or V.

After analyzing these 2 graphs and the relative error graph, the approximation rank I would choose to compress this image would probably be somewhere around 20-30. These values of k seems to gather the most amount of information while keeping the compression rate relatively low.
